          "body": "The transition from 2:10 to 2:11 is one of the Bible's most compressed narrative jumps. An infant becomes an adult between two verses. When Moses 'went out to his brethren' (2:11), the verb indicates a deliberate choice — he did not stumble upon the labor gangs but chose to go and look. What he saw and how he responded reveals a man who knows who he is (he calls them 'his brethren' twice in 2:11) but does not yet know how to act. The Egyptian beating a Hebrew provokes an immediate and violent response: Moses looks to see if anyone is watching — a gesture of moral anxiety, not moral authority — and then kills the Egyptian and buries him in the sand (2:12). Stephen in Acts 7:25 reads Moses's motive charitably: 'He supposed that his brethren understood that God was granting them deliverance through him.' The instinct is right; the method and the timing are entirely wrong. The next day exposes the failure: a Hebrew challenges his authority ('Who made you a ruler and judge over us?', 2:14), and the concealment unravels instantly. Moses is afraid (2:14) — the first time the word *yare* applies to him. The future leader of the Exodus is currently a frightened fugitive who has accomplished nothing except to prove he cannot yet be trusted with the task he senses is his."
