        {
          "title": "Midian — exile as the school of God",
          "body": "Moses's arrival at the well in Midian (2:15) is a scene any reader of Genesis would recognize immediately. A displaced man, at a well, meets women in need, intervenes to help, is invited to eat, receives a wife — this is the type-scene of Genesis 24 (Abraham's servant and Rebekah), Genesis 29 (Jacob and Rachel), and now Exodus 2 (Moses and Zipporah). The narrator is not being repetitive; he is signaling that Moses's story is continuous with the patriarchal story, and that the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob is the same God operating here. The detail that Reuel has seven daughters and that the shepherds 'drove them away' (2:17) positions the daughters as victims in need of a defender — which is exactly what Moses has been trying to be, badly, in Egypt. Here in Midian, without Egyptian rank or royal connection, he simply stands up and helps (2:17). The outcome is a wife, a son, and a name: Gershom, 'a sojourner in a foreign land' (2:22). Moses lives in the self-knowledge that he is displaced — not Egyptian enough for Egypt, not ready enough for Israel. The exile is not wasted time. It is forty years of shepherding (Acts 7:30), which is precisely the preparation God is shaping for a man who will spend forty years leading sheep through the same wilderness."
        },
        {
          "title": "God's four verbs — the theological frame of the whole chapter",
          "body": "Exodus 2:23-25 is three verses, four verbs, and the most important theological statement in the chapter. After 22 verses of human action — mothers hiding, daughters scheming, Moses killing, shepherds bullying, and a fugitive settling — God appears. And He appears not in a vision or a voice, but in four verbs: *heard*, *remembered*, *saw*, *took notice* (or in some translations, 'knew'). The theological architecture is precise. First, God *heard* the groaning — Israel does not pray a prayer; they groan under bondage, and the groan ascends to God (2:23). Second, God *remembered* His covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob — not because He had forgotten, but because *zakhar* in the Hebrew covenantal vocabulary means engaged, purposeful attention that moves toward fulfillment. 'To remember' in the Old Testament is always to act (Genesis 8:1; 9:15; 30:22). Third, God *saw* the sons of Israel — the same verb that the mother used when she looked at Moses (2:2), the same verb Moses used to survey the labor gangs (2:11). God's seeing is not passive observation but active involvement. Fourth, God *took notice* of them — the Hebrew *yada*, to know, is the deepest relational verb in the Old Testament, used of the intimate knowledge between persons. These four verbs frame the entire chapter retroactively: the basket in the Nile was inside God's hearing. The mother's wages were inside God's seeing. Moses's exile in Midian was inside God's remembering. Nothing in the human story was outside the divine story. The chapter that appeared to be about Moses's failed formation ends by revealing it was always about a covenant-keeping God whose purpose the failures of human history cannot derail."
        }
